England, United Kingdom","Witherslock Manor, Westmorelandshire, England":"Westmorland, England, United Kingdom","Witherslack, Westmorland, England":"Witherslack, Westmorland, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Castle Lancaster, Hempsfield, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thornborough","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from any of various places, including Thornborough in Allerton Mauleverer (WR Yorks), Thornbrough in South Kilvington (NR Yorks), Thornbrough in Corbridge (Northumb), and Thornborough (Bucks).  See also  Thornbury   and   Thornber  .","2  Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’;  compare  Thornton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thornborrow","meanings":["English:  see  Thornborough  ."]},{"name":"Thornton","meanings":["English and Scottish: habitational name from any of numerous places throughout England and Scotland so called, from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn tree’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The placename is most frequent in northern England, especially Yorkshire, where there are at least 16 possible sources for the surname.","Irish: Anglicized (translated) form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Sceachán</i>’ (see   Skehan  ).","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Draighneáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Draighneán</i>’ (see   Drennan  )."]},{"name":"Thornburrow","meanings":["English:  see  Thornborough  ."]},{"name":"Thornbury","meanings":["English: variant of   Thornberry  .","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornber","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of the five minor places in Yorkshire called Thornber, particularly Thornber in Halton West. The placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>beorg</i> ‘hill, mound’.","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornberry","meanings":["English (southwestern): habitational name from any of various places called Thornbury, in particular Thornbury (Gloucestershire), Thornbury (Herefordshire), or perhaps Thornbury (Devon), or Thornbury in Bradford (Yorkshire). These placenames derive from Old English <i>thorn</i> ‘thorn’ + <i>burg</i> ‘fortress’ or ‘manor’.","English: variant of   Thornber  .","Irish: adopted for various Irish names containing an element meaning ‘thorn’; compare   Thornton  ."]},{"name":"Thornbery","meanings":["English:  see  Thornborough  ."]},{"name":"Thornburgh","meanings":["English (Worcestershire) and Irish: variant of   Thornbury  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."],"variants":[{"name":"Anni","meanings":["Pet form of   Ann   or   Anne ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Thornborough was born in 1440, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir William  Rowland Thornborough, was 10 and her mother, Margaret Middleton, was 45. She had at least 1 daughter with Thomas de Ros. She died in 1525, in her hometown, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1440–1525":"1440–1525","1430–1465":"1430–1465","1465–1510":"1465–1510","1430–1444":"1430–1444","1395–Female":"1395–Surnud","1525":"1525","17 May 1465":"17. mai 1465","1444":"1444","1510":"1510","1465":"1465","1430":"1430","1440":"1440","1395":"1395","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Witherslock Manor, Westmorelandshire, England":"Westmorland, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Witherslack, Westmorland, England":"Witherslack, Westmorland, England","Lan